{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12346"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12346"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.15,0.04,0.71,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4866"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63949"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1383"},{"type":"tags","id":"1664"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26728"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-month-old child is brought to a general practice for a routine checkup. The mother is happy with her daughter\u0027s progress. She is feeding well and gaining weight. As the doctor begins her examination, she notices the appearance of the child\u0027s eyes (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn general examination, patient is irritable, there is swelling and restricted right eye movement. There is decreased vision in the right eye, and she is unable to focus on things. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior persistent hyperplastic primary vitreous","Congenital cataract","Retrolental fibroplasia","Retinoblastoma","Coat\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child has leukocoria (white pupil). This can be a sign of an underlying life-threatening disease, so the general practitioner needs to refer the child that same day to a paediatric hospital for an urgent ophthalmic assessment, diagnosis and probable co-management with paediatric oncology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely explanation for the leukocoria in this case is an underlying \u003Cstrong\u003Eretinoblastoma.\u003C/strong\u003E Not only is there leukocoria, but there is swelling and restricted movement of the eye. Typically, these patients will have delayed milestones and present either with leukocoria, a squint or decreased vision. Ophthalmoscopic examination will show calcium deposition on the surface of the tumour, which appears white pearly and within the tumour appears chalky white. There will be increased intraocular pressure on tonometry and an MRI will define the tumour, which may have optic nerve and/or extraocular involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior persistent hyperplastic primary vitreous (APHPV) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a disease in which the primary vitreous, which contains the hyaloid vascular system for nutrition of the developing lens, fails to regress and present as a white mass at the back of the lens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital cataract\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of leukocoria. Congenital rubella is probably the most frequent cause of congenital cataract. Patients present with decreased vision and there will be a whitish reflex in pupillary area, together with nystagmus. However, in this case there are the additional signs of swelling and restricted movement of the affected eye, making a congenital cataract a less likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetrolental fibroplasia \u003C/strong\u003Eis a retinopathy that occurs in premature infants due to oxygen toxicity, resulting in a fibrovascular mass behind the lens. Common symptoms include are visual disturbance, retinal detachment, absent papillary light reflexes and potential blindness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoat\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital retinal vascular abnormality in which there is leakage from vessels, resulting into exudation and retinal detachment. Although rare, it occurs much more often in males than females. Fluorescein angiography discloses early hyperfluorescence of the telangiectasias and macular oedema. Ultrasonography typically showed a retinal detachment, but no solid mass.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignancy of childhood.","Leukocoria, or a white pupillary reflex, is a key clinical sign that may indicate retinoblastoma.","Early detection and referral for retinoblastoma are crucial for preserving vision and preventing metastasis."],"references":["Ishaq H, Patel BC. Retinoblastoma. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31424860. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31424860/","Dimaras H, Corson TW, Cobrinik D, White A, Zhao J, Munier FL, Abramson DH, Shields CL, Chantada GL, Njuguna F, Gallie BL. Retinoblastoma. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2015 Aug 27;1:15021. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2015.21. PMID: 27189421; PMCID: PMC5744255. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5744255/","Byroju VV, Nadukkandy AS, Cordani M, Kumar LD. Retinoblastoma: present scenario and future challenges. Cell Commun Signal. 2023 Sep 4;21(1):226. doi: 10.1186/s12964-023-01223-z. PMID: 37667345; PMCID: PMC10478474. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10478474/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63949"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12346"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19135"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19135"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/30bfc963-66fe-431a-bd23-42c7b40eda85.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/30bfc963-66fe-431a-bd23-42c7b40eda85.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":391}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63949"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T18:16:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T18:16:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4866"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t